MORE ABOUT BURMA:

The people of Burma have been under the totalitarian rule of a military junta
since 1962. In 1988, millions of people took to the streets to demand
democracy. In response, the military slaughtered over 2,000 Burmese
pro-democracy demonstrators, including school children, Buddhist monks and
students. Due to pressure from the international community, the military
government was forced to hold multi-party legislative elections in May, 1990.

Daw Aung Suu Kyi, one of the prodemocracy movement, formed the National League
for Democracy (NLD). Even though she had been under arrest since 1989 the NLD
won the 1990 elections in a landslide. The NLD won 82% of the seats in the
National Assembly but the military government refused to relinquish power.
Immediate following the elections, SLORC cracked down by arresting elected
NLD officials and building militarybases in every municipality - effectively
turning Burna into a police state; today, there are over 30,000 political
prisoners in Burma.

SLORC will remain vulnerable to foreign divestment. Its brutal and illegal
rule depends on foreign investors for cash, technical aid and the pretense of
"political neutrality"  - without the crutch of foreign assistance, SLORC is
likely to collapse, as did the apartheid regime in South Africa.

